<p>List Image
<img src="https://i.stack.imgur.com/ER0l2.png" alt="enter image description here"></p> <p>Instead of overriding your custom adapter's <code>onClick</code> method and executing your <code>AsyncTask</code> from there, attach an OnClickListener while you define your Button within the <code>getView()</code> method. For example, while defining your <code>Buttons</code> within your <code>getView()</code> method: </p>
<pre><code>public View getView(int i, View view, ViewGroup viewGroup) {
if (view == null) 
{
view = LayoutInflater.from (c).inflate (R.layout.custom_search_jobs_lists, viewGroup, false);
}
Button bestCandidate = (Button) view.findViewById (R.id.bt_best_candidates);
bestCandidate.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener(){
@Override
public void onClick(View v) {
// Start your AsyncTask here.
} 
}); 
Button appliedJobs = (Button) view.findViewById (R.id.bt_applied_jobs);
appliedJobs.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener(){
@Override
public void onClick(View v) {
// Start your AsyncTask here.
} 
}); 
........
} // end of getView()
</code></pre>
<p>An advantage of this approach is that it ensures that you needn't worry about finding the positions of the list item elements that contain the buttons which were clicked during execution time as they are bound to the view (list item) that is inflated by your <code>LayoutInflater</code> in your <code>getView()</code> method. There is also a good chance that your list may expand beyond the size of the screen causing your <code>ListView</code> to recycle its elements, meaning that if for example you want to change the background-color of your list item on a Button click, you will experiece unexpected results. Implementing your <code>OnClickListeners</code> within the <code>getView()</code> method can also help you manage this situation by manipulating the positions of the list items within the <code>getView()</code> method itself as it is readily available as an argument of the method. </p>

